    <text>
        <body>
            <head>139. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="1" place="foot" type="source"
                    xml:id="d139fn1">Source: Department of State, Lot 90D397, Ambassador <persName
                        corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu">Nitze</persName>’s Personal Files 1953,
                    1972–1989, Box 4, 1986 July–Aug. Secret; Sensitive. The meeting took place in
                    the <gloss target="#t_EUR_1">EUR</gloss> Conference Room at the Department of
                    State. Brackets are in the original.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1986-07-25T15:40:00-04:00">July 25, 1986, 3:40 p.m.</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="participants">
                <item>
                    <list>
                        <head>
                            <hi rendition="simple_italic">U.S. PARTICIPANTS</hi>
                        </head>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_EUR_1">EUR</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_DAS_1"
                                >DAS</gloss>
                            <persName corresp="recBbyyU6ZEkgteau">Thomas Simons</persName>
                        </item>
                        <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu">Paul Nitze</persName>
                        </item>
                        <item>COL <persName corresp="rec3WaAgwEDeqcFLV">Robert Linhard</persName>
                                (<gloss target="#t_NSC_1">
                                <orgName corresp="recft7WGb7Fww0wma">NSC</orgName>
                            </gloss>)</item>
                        <item>SOV Director <persName corresp="recVITvpjZsQaZWYz">Mark
                                Parris</persName>
                        </item>
                        <item>SOV Dep Dir <persName corresp="recpqjVOqbV3HTKro">Bruce
                                Burton</persName> (notetaker)</item>
                    </list>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <list>
                        <head>
                            <hi rendition="simple_italic">SOVIET PARTICIPANTS</hi>
                        </head>
                        <item>Deputy ForMin <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC"
                                >Bessmertnykh</persName>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_DCM_1">DCM</gloss>
                            <persName corresp="rec0RifsbSwSdWTi3">Oleg Sokolov</persName>
                        </item>
                        <item>Minister-Counselor <persName corresp="recJpBGuhe4SXmHoo">Victor
                                Isakov</persName>
                        </item>
                        <item>Counselor <persName corresp="rec4oFoFLwJ6JCkwV">Vadim
                                Kuznetsov</persName>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p>
                <persName corresp="recBbyyU6ZEkgteau">Simons</persName> opened by welcoming
                    <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Bessmertnykh</persName> to Washington and
                congratulating him on his appointment as deputy foreign minister. <persName
                    corresp="recBbyyU6ZEkgteau">Simons</persName> then handed him the signed
                original of the <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">President</persName>’s
                    letter<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d139fn2">See <ref target="#d138">Document
                        138</ref>.</note> and said it was being delivered nearly simultaneously in
                Moscow. <pb facs="0581" n="554" xml:id="pg_554"/>
                <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Bessmertnykh</persName> and company took about
                15 minutes to read the letter. After doing so, <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC"
                    >Bessmertnykh</persName> said he had an “urge to say something but I think I
                won’t”. He commented that this was a crucial time in <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recpotPshsDR78MFp">U.S.-Soviet relations</rs> and we would discuss the
                letter later, but he thought the main point of <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq"
                    >the President</persName>’s proposal seemed to be to allow testing of
                space-based systems without limitations.</p>
            <p>
                <persName corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu">Nitze</persName> answered that this
                interpretation was incorrect. <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">The
                    President</persName> is saying that <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recFUg0jqFk2tUZ15">testing</rs> and development, which is permitted by
                the <gloss target="#t_ABM_1">ABM</gloss> Treaty, will continue. <persName
                    corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu">Nitze</persName> continued that some <rs
                    type="compound-subject" corresp="recFUg0jqFk2tUZ15">testing</rs> and development
                is permitted by the treaty, and some is not; both sides can do what is permitted.
                    <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Bessmertnykh</persName> asked if that
                meant we could “test and develop only what is permitted,” and <persName
                    corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu">Nitze</persName> answered that was correct.
                    <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Bessmertnykh</persName> then commented
                that “it comes again to the question of defining what is permitted by the
                treaty.”</p>
            <p>
                <persName corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu">Nitze</persName> emphasized that <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName> intends to advance the
                process of discussions and believes that it is important to make a move forward. He
                said <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName> had tried to
                take into account the concerns of both sides. The proposal itself demonstrates
                    <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName>’s desire to
                address the issues broadly. <persName corresp="recZmD7Wil34KIjtu">Nitze</persName>
                added that it also our intent to move forward on the purpose of <persName
                    corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Bessmertnykh</persName>’s visit, i.e., to organize
                the work ahead. <persName corresp="recBbyyU6ZEkgteau">Simons</persName> added that
                we want a thorough discussion of all areas in <rs type="compound-subject"
                    corresp="recpotPshsDR78MFp">U.S.-Soviet relations</rs>.</p>
            <p>
                <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Bessmertnykh</persName>, referring to the
                passage in <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName>’s letter
                which said the U.S. would present the new proposal at the <gloss target="#t_NST_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">NST</rs>
                </gloss> negotiations, then asked if there was any chance for a “working” meeting on
                    <gloss target="#t_NST_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recdBCWoByS1vPFiZ">NST</rs>
                </gloss> before the round formally opens on September 18. He suggested a meeting of
                a small group of three or four experts on each side, not necessarily at the
                    <persName corresp="recTyVVS5UdJjYopp">Karpov</persName>-<persName
                    corresp="rectgy2hXleek4j6N">Kampelman</persName> level, since that would give
                the appearance of formal talks. <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC"
                    >Bessmertnykh</persName> said he realized that we were not going to develop a
                treaty in the next few months but we need to examine the issues closely. <persName
                    corresp="recBbyyU6ZEkgteau">Simons</persName>, referring to <persName
                    corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName>’s conversation with former
                Ambassador <persName corresp="rec62rNu2glRunbNq">Dobrynin</persName> in April,<note
                    n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d139fn3">Reference is to <persName
                        corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName>’s meeting with <persName
                        corresp="rec62rNu2glRunbNq">Dobrynin</persName> on April 8. The memorandum
                    of conversation is scheduled for publication in <ref
                        target="frus1981-88v05#d212">
                        <hi rendition="simple_italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1981–1988, vol. V,
                        Soviet Union, March 1985–October 1986, Document 212</ref>.</note> said
                    <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Bessmertnykh</persName>’s suggestion made
                sense and that we saw <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC"
                >Bessmertnykh</persName>’s visit as a chance to initiate such discussions.</p>
            <p>
                <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Bessmertnykh</persName>, turning to <persName
                    corresp="rec3WaAgwEDeqcFLV">Linhard</persName>, asked the origin of the
                references in <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">the President</persName>’s
                letter to banning <rs type="topic" corresp="recejU7I7gSPAJNQp">space-based
                    weapons</rs> of mass destruction. <persName corresp="rec3WaAgwEDeqcFLV"
                    >Linhard</persName> started to answer that this was a subject raised at the
                summit and in the Geneva talks, but <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC"
                    >Bessmertnykh</persName> broke in to quip that since the U.S. and Soviet Union
                already had a treaty [i.e., the <pb facs="0582" n="555" xml:id="pg_555"/>
                <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recEptOG33vXPFGSR">Outer Space Treaty</rs>]
                on this, the presence of so many references in <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq"
                    >the President</persName>’s letter to <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recejU7I7gSPAJNQp">space-based weapons</rs> of mass destruction began
                to make him nervous.</p>
            <p>
                <persName corresp="recBbyyU6ZEkgteau">Simons</persName> then said that the American
                press was aware that <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Bessmertnykh</persName>
                was here. We intended to answer queries by noting that <persName
                    corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Bessmertnykh</persName> was in Washington for a
                review of <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recpotPshsDR78MFp">U.S.-Soviet
                    relations</rs> and that we hoped the visit would provide new energy to our
                discussions. If the media sought to portray the visit as a special event, we would
                say it was special only because it was being held at the deputy foreign minister
                level, but that it was a part of a process of exchanges the two sides had agreed to
                and had been conducting for some time.</p>
            <p>
                <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC">Bessmertnykh</persName>, laughing, then said
                he had something to bring up. At the May talks on <orgName
                    corresp="recWmlQ0xSSemmPRz">nuclear risk reduction centers</orgName> [NRCC], the
                U.S. had proposed that a second round be held at the end of July. The Soviets, he
                said, would like to propose that the NRCC experts meet in Geneva on July 29–30—and
                the Soviets needed an answer that evening. <persName corresp="rec3WaAgwEDeqcFLV"
                    >Linhard</persName> answered that, at the May meeting, the two sides seemed to
                agree that the experts talks were intended to explore the concept of risk reduction
                centers and that we would not rush the issue. In any case, the U.S. had offered to
                host the next meeting in Washington, although we were flexible on venue. It was
                pointed out that a meeting next week would pose difficulties but that we would get
                back to the Soviets as soon as possible. <persName corresp="rec7xweQJwHGxmZDC"
                    >Bessmertnykh</persName> seemed to indicate that one factor in the Soviet
                suggestion was that Ambassador <persName corresp="recpzeNUmrT8bK2yc"
                    >Obukhov</persName> will be in Geneva next week.</p>
        </body>
